(lp3
VIn December of 2010,
p4
aVthe city of Apatzingán
p5
aVin the coastal state of Michoacán, in Mexico,
p6
aVawoke to gunfire.
p7
aVFor two straight days,
p8
aVthe city became an open battlefield
p9
aVbetween the federal forces
p10
aVand a well-organized group,
p11
aVpresumably from the local criminal organization,
p12
aVLa Familia Michoacana, or the Michoacán family.
p13
aVThe citizens didn't only experience incessant gunfire
p14
aVbut also explosions
p15
aVand burning trucks used as barricades across the city,
p16
aVso truly like a battlefield.
p17
aVAfter these two days,
p18
aVand during a particularly intense encounter,
p19
aVit was presumed that the leader of La Familia Michoacana,
p20
aVNazario Moreno, was killed.
p21
aa(lp22
VIn response to this terrifying violence,
p23
aVthe mayor of Apatzingán
p24
aVdecided to call the citizens to a march for peace.
p25
aVThe idea was to ask for a softer approach
p26
aVto criminal activity in the state.
p27
aVAnd so, the day of the scheduled procession,
p28
aVthousands of people showed up.
p29
aVAs the mayor was preparing to deliver
p30
aVthe speech starting the march,
p31
aVhis team noticed
p32
aVthat, while half of the participants
p33
aVwere appropriately dressed in white,
p34
aVand bearing banners asking for peace,
p35
aVthe other half was actually marching
p36
aVin support of the criminal organization
p37
aVand its now-presumed-defunct leader.
p38
aVShocked, the mayor decided to step aside
p39
aVrather than participate or lead a procession
p40
aVthat was ostensibly in support of organized crime.
p41
aVAnd so his team stepped aside.
p42
aVThe two marches joined together,
p43
aVand they continued their path
p44
aVtowards the state capital.
p45
aa(lp46
VThis story of horrific violence
p47
aVfollowed by a fumbled approach
p48
aVby federal and local authorities as they tried
p49
aVto engage civil society,
p50
aVwho has been very well engaged by a criminal organization,
p51
aVis a perfect metaphor for what's happening in Mexico today,
p52
aVwhere we see that our current understanding
p53
aVof drug violence and what leads to it
p54
aVis probably at the very least incomplete.
p55
aa(lp56
VIf you decided to spend 30 minutes trying
p57
aVto figure out what's going on with drug violence in Mexico
p58
aVby, say, just researching online,
p59
aVthe first thing you would find out is that
p60
aVwhile the laws state that all Mexican citizens are equal,
p61
aVthere are some that are more
p62
aVand there are some that are much less equal than others,
p63
aVbecause you will quickly find out
p64
aVthat in the past six years
p65
aVanywhere between 60 and 100,000 people
p66
aVhave lost their lives in drug-related violence.
p67
aVTo put these numbers in perspective,
p68
aVthis is eight times larger than the number of casualties
p69
aVin the Iraq and Afghanistan wars combined.
p70
aVIt's also shockingly close to the number of people
p71
aVwho have died in the Syrian civil war,
p72
aVwhich is an active civil war.
p73
aVThis is happening just south of the border.
p74
aa(lp75
VNow as you're reading, however,
p76
aVyou will be maybe surprised that you will quickly
p77
aVbecome numb to the numbers of deaths,
p78
aVbecause you will see that these are sort of abstract numbers
p79
aVof faceless, nameless dead people.
p80
aVImplicitly or explicitly, there is a narrative
p81
aVthat all the people who are dying
p82
aVwere somehow involved in the drug trade,
p83
aVand we infer this because they were either tortured
p84
aVor executed in a professional manner,
p85
aVor, most likely, both.
p86
aVAnd so clearly they were criminals
p87
aVbecause of the way they died.
p88
aVAnd so the narrative is that somehow these people
p89
aVgot what they were deserved.
p90
aVThey were part of the bad guys.
p91
aVAnd that creates some form of comfort
p92
aVfor a lot of people.
p93
aa(lp94
VHowever, while it's easier to think
p95
aVof us, the citizens, the police, the army,
p96
aVas the good guys, and them, the narcos,
p97
aVthe carteles, as the bad guys,
p98
aVif you think about it,
p99
aVthe latter are only providing a service to the former.
p100
aVWhether we like it or not,
p101
aVthe U.S. is the largest market
p102
aVfor illegal substances in the world,
p103
aVaccounting for more than half of global demand.
p104
aVIt shares thousands of miles of border with Mexico
p105
aVthat is its only route of access from the South,
p106
aVand so, as the former dictator of Mexico, Porfirio Diaz,
p107
aVused to say, "Poor Mexico,
p108
aVso far from God and so close to the United States."
p109
aa(lp110
VThe U.N. estimates that there are 55 million users
p111
aVof illegal drugs in the United States.
p112
aVUsing very, very conservative assumptions,
p113
aVthis yields a yearly drug market on the retail side
p114
aVof anywhere between 30 and 150 billion dollars.
p115
aVIf we assume that the narcos only have access
p116
aVto the wholesale part, which we know is false,
p117
aVthat still leaves you with yearly revenues
p118
aVof anywhere between 15 billion and 60 billion dollars.
p119
aVTo put these numbers in perspective,
p120
aVMicrosoft has yearly revenues of 60 billion dollars.
p121
aVAnd it so happens that this is a product that,
p122
aVbecause of its nature, a business model
p123
aVto address this market requires you
p124
aVto guarantee to your producers
p125
aVthat their product will be reliably placed
p126
aVin the markets where it is consumed.
p127
aVAnd the only way to do this, because it's illegal,
p128
aVis to have absolute control of the geographic corridors
p129
aVthat are used to transport drugs.
p130
aVHence the violence.
p131
aVIf you look at a map of cartel influence and violence,
p132
aVyou will see that it almost perfectly aligns
p133
aVwith the most efficient routes of transportation
p134
aVfrom the south to the north.
p135
aVThe only thing that the cartels are doing
p136
aVis that they're trying to protect their business.
p137
aa(lp138
VIt's not only a multi-billion dollar market,
p139
aVbut it's also a complex one.
p140
aVFor example, the coca plant is a fragile plant
p141
aVthat can only grow in certain latitudes,
p142
aVand so it means that a business model
p143
aVto address this market requires you to have
p144
aVdecentralized, international production,
p145
aVthat by the way needs to have good quality control,
p146
aVbecause people need a good high
p147
aVthat is not going to kill them
p148
aVand that is going to be delivered to them when they need it.
p149
aVAnd so that means they need to secure
p150
aVproduction and quality control in the south,
p151
aVand you need to ensure that you have
p152
aVefficient and effective distribution channels
p153
aVin the markets where these drugs are consumed.
p154
aVI urge you, but only a little bit,
p155
aVbecause I don't want to get you in trouble,
p156
aVto just ask around and see how difficult it would be
p157
aVto get whatever drug you want, wherever you want it,
p158
aVwhenever you want it, anywhere in the U.S.,
p159
aVand some of you may be surprised to know
p160
aVthat there are many dealers that offer a service
p161
aVwhere if you send them a text message,
p162
aVthey guarantee delivery of the drug
p163
aVin 30 minutes or less.
p164
aa(lp165
VThink about this for a second.
p166
aVThink about the complexity
p167
aVof the distribution network that I just described.
p168
aVIt's very difficult to reconcile this
p169
aVwith the image of faceless, ignorant goons
p170
aVthat are just shooting each other,
p171
aVvery difficult to reconcile.
