aa(lp173
VNow, as a business professor, and as any business professor would tell you,
p174
aVan effective organization requires
p175
aVan integrated strategy that includes
p176
aVa good organizational structure, good incentives,
p177
aVa solid identity and good brand management.
p178
aVThis leads me to the second thing that you would learn
p179
aVin your 30-minute exploration of drug violence in Mexico.
p180
aVBecause you would quickly realize,
p181
aVand maybe be confused by the fact,
p182
aVthat there are three organizations
p183
aVthat are constantly named in the articles.
p184
aVYou will hear about Los Zetas,
p185
aVthe Knights Templar, which is the new brand
p186
aVfor the Familia Michoacana that I spoke about at the beginning,
p187
aVand the Sinaloa Federation.
p188
aVYou will read that Los Zetas is this assortment
p189
aVof sociopaths that terrify the cities that they enter
p190
aVand they silence the press,
p191
aVand this is somewhat true, or mostly true.
p192
aVBut this is the result of a very careful branding
p193
aVand business strategy.
p194
aVYou see, Los Zetas is not just
p195
aVthis random assortment of individuals,
p196
aVbut was actually created by another criminal organization, the Gulf Cartel,
p197
aVthat used to control the eastern corridor of Mexico.
p198
aVWhen that corridor became contested, they decided
p199
aVthat they wanted to recruit
p200
aVa professional enforcement arm.
p201
aVSo they recruited Los Zetas:
p202
aVan entire unit of elite paratroopers
p203
aVfrom the Mexican Army.
p204
aVThey were incredibly effective as enforcers for the Gulf Cartel,
p205
aVso much so that at some point, they decided
p206
aVto just take over the operations,
p207
aVwhich is why I ask you to never keep tigers as pets,
p208
aVbecause they grow up.
p209
aVBecause the Zetas organization was founded in treason,
p210
aVthey lost some of the linkages to the production and distribution
p211
aVin the most profitable markets like cocaine,
p212
aVbut what they did have,
p213
aVand this is again based on their military origin,
p214
aVwas a perfectly structured chain of command
p215
aVwith a very clear hierarchy
p216
aVand a very clear promotion path that allowed them
p217
aVto supervise and operate across many, many markets
p218
aVvery effectively,
p219
aVwhich is the essence of what a chain of command seeks to do.
p220
aVAnd so because they didn't have access
p221
aVto the more profitable drug markets,
p222
aVthis pushed them and gave them the opportunity
p223
aVto diversify into other forms of crime.
p224
aVThat includes kidnapping, prostitution,
p225
aVlocal drug dealing and human trafficking,
p226
aVincluding of migrants that go from the south to the U.S.
p227
aVSo what they currently run is truly
p228
aVand quite literally a franchise business.
p229
aVThey focus most of their recruiting on the army,
p230
aVand they very openly advertise for better salaries,
p231
aVbetter benefits, better promotion paths,
p232
aVnot to mention much better food,
p233
aVthan what the army can deliver.
p234
aVThe way they operate is that
p235
aVwhen they arrive in a locality,
p236
aVthey let people know that they are there,
p237
aVand they go to the most powerful local gang
p238
aVand they say, "I offer you
p239
aVto be the local representative of the Zeta brand."
p240
aVIf they agree \u2014 and you don't want to know
p241
aVwhat happens if they don't \u2014
p242
aVthey train them and they supervise them
p243
aVon how to run the most efficient criminal operation
p244
aVfor that town, in exchange for royalties.
p245
aVThis kind of business model obviously depends
p246
aVentirely on having a very effective brand of fear,
p247
aVand so Los Zetas
p248
aVcarefully stage acts of violence
p249
aVthat are spectacular in nature,
p250
aVespecially when they arrive first in a city,
p251
aVbut again, that's just a brand strategy.
p252
aVI'm not saying they're not violent,
p253
aVbut what I am saying is that even though you will read
p254
aVthat they are the most violent of all,
p255
aVwhen you count, when you do the body count,
p256
aVthey're actually all the same.
p257
aa(lp258
VIn contrast to them, the Knights Templar
p259
aVthat arose in Michoacán
p260
aVemerged in reaction to the incursion
p261
aVof the Zetas into the state of Michoacán.
p262
aVMichoacán is a geographically strategic state
p263
aVbecause it has one of the largest ports in Mexico,
p264
aVand it has very direct routes to the center of Mexico,
p265
aVwhich then gives you direct access to the U.S.
p266
aVThe Knights Templar realized very quickly
p267
aVthat they couldn't face the Zetas on violence alone,
p268
aVand so they developed a strategy
p269
aVas a social enterprise.
p270
aVThey brand themselves as representative of
p271
aVand protecting of the citizens of Michoacán
p272
aVagainst organized crime.
p273
aVTheir brand of social enterprise means
p274
aVthat they require a lot of civic engagement,
p275
aVso they invest heavily in providing local services,
p276
aVlike dealing with home violence,
p277
aVgoing after petty criminals, treating addicts,
p278
aVand keeping drugs out of the local markets
p279
aVwhere they are,
p280
aVand, of course, protecting people
p281
aVfrom other criminal organizations.
p282
aVNow, they kill a lot of people too,
p283
aVbut when they kill them,
p284
aVthey provide very careful narratives and descriptions
p285
aVfor why they did them,
p286
aVthrough newspaper insertions, YouTube videos,
p287
aVand billboards that explain that the people who were killed
p288
aVwere killed because they represented a threat
p289
aVnot to us, as an organization, of course,
p290
aVbut to you, as citizens.
p291
aVAnd so we're actually here to protect you.
p292
aVThey, as social enterprises do,
p293
aVhave created a moral and ethical code
p294
aVthat they advertise around,
p295
aVand they have very strict recruiting practices.
p296
aVAnd here you have the types of explanations
p297
aVthat they provide for some of their actions.
p298
aVThey have actually retained access
p299
aVto the profitable drug trade,
p300
aVbut the way they do it is, because they control all of Michoacán,
p301
aVand they control the Port of Lázaro Cárdenas,
p302
aVthey leverage that to, for example,
p303
aVtrade copper from Michoacán that is legally created
p304
aVand legally extracted
p305
aVwith illegal ephedrine from China
p306
aVwhich is a critical precursor for methamphetamines
p307
aVthat they produce, and then they have partnerships
p308
aVwith larger organizations like the Sinaloa Federation
p309
aVthat place their products in the U.S.
p310
aa(lp311
VFinally, the Sinaloa Federation.
p312
aVWhen you read about them, you will often read about them
p313
aVwith an undertone of reverence and admiration,
p314
aVbecause they are the most integrated
p315
aVand the largest of all the Mexican organizations,
p316
aVand, many people argue, the world.
p317
aVThey started as just sort of a transport organization
p318
aVthat specialized in smuggling between the U.S.
p319
aVand the Mexican borders,
p320
aVbut now they have grown
p321
aVinto a truly integrated multinational
p322
aVthat has partnerships in production in the south
p323
aVand partnerships in global distribution
p324
aVacross the planet.
p325
aVThey have cultivated a brand of professionalism,
p326
aVbusiness acumen and innovation.
p327
aVThey have designed new drug products
p328
aVand new drug processes.
p329
aVThey have designed narco-tunnels
p330
aVthat go across the border,
p331
aVand you can see that these are not
p332
aV"The Shawshank Redemption" types.
p333
aVThey have invented narco-submarines and boats
p334
aVthat are not detected by radar.
p335
aVThey have invented drones to transport drugs,
p336
aVcatapults, you name it.
p337
aVOne of the leaders of the Sinaloa Federation
p338
aVactually made it to the Forbes list.
