aa(lp340
V[#701 Joaquin Guzman Loera]
p341
aa(lp342
VLike any multinational would, they have specialized
p343
aVand focused only in the most profitable part of the business,
p344
aVwhich is high-margin drugs like cocaine,
p345
aVheroine, methamphetamines.
p346
aVLike any traditional Latin American multinational would,
p347
aVthe way they control their operations
p348
aVis through family ties.
p349
aVWhen they're entering a new market, they send
p350
aVa family member to supervise it,
p351
aVor, if they're partnering with a new organization,
p352
aVthey create a family tie,
p353
aVeither through marriages or other types of ties.
p354
aVLike any other multinational would,
p355
aVthey protect their brand by outsourcing
p356
aVthe more questionable parts of the business model,
p357
aVlike for example, when they have to engage
p358
aVin violence against other criminal organizations,
p359
aVthey recruit gangs and other smaller players
p360
aVto do the dirty work for them,
p361
aVand they try to separate their operations
p362
aVand their violence and be very discrete about this.
p363
aa(lp364
VTo further strengthen their brand,
p365
aVthey actually have professional P.R. firms
p366
aVthat shape how the press talks about them.
p367
aVThey have professional videographers on staff.
p368
aVThey have incredibly productive ties
p369
aVwith the security organizations
p370
aVon both sides of the border.
p371
aa(lp372
VAnd so, differences aside,
p373
aVwhat these three organizations share
p374
aVis on the one hand, a very clear understanding
p375
aVthat institutions cannot be imposed from the top,
p376
aVbut rather they are built from the bottom up
p377
aVone interaction at a time.
p378
aVThey have created extremely coherent structures
p379
aVthat they use to show the inconsistencies
p380
aVin government policies.
p381
aa(lp382
VAnd so what I want you to remember from this talk
p383
aVare three things.
p384
aVThe first one is that drug violence
p385
aVis actually the result
p386
aVof a huge market demand
p387
aVand an institutional setup that forces
p388
aVthe servicing of this market to necessitate violence
p389
aVto guarantee delivery routes.
p390
aVThe second thing I want you to remember
p391
aVis that these are sophisticated,
p392
aVcoherent organizations
p393
aVthat are business organizations,
p394
aVand analyzing them and treating them as such
p395
aVis probably a much more useful approach.
p396
aVThe third thing I want you to remember
p397
aVis that even though we're more comfortable
p398
aVwith this idea of "them,"
p399
aVa set of bad guys separated from us,
p400
aVwe are actually accomplices to them,
p401
aVeither through our direct consumption
p402
aVor through our acceptance of the inconsistency
p403
aVbetween our policies of prohibition
p404
aVand our actual behavior of tolerance
p405
aVor even encouragement of consumption.
p406
aa(lp407
VThese organizations service, recruit from,
p408
aVand operate within our communities,
p409
aVso necessarily, they are much more integrated
p410
aVwithin them than we are comfortable acknowledging.
p411
aVAnd so to me the question is not whether
p412
aVthese dynamics will continue the way they have.
p413
aVWe see that the nature of this phenomenon
p414
aVguarantees that they will.
p415
aVThe question is whether we are willing to continue
p416
aVour support of a failed strategy
p417
aVbased on our stubborn, blissful, voluntary ignorance
p418
aVat the cost of the deaths of thousands of our young.
